<speciesPage><NAME_CD>VP-136</NAME_CD><group>PLANT</group><desc><growthForm>Perennial aquatic herb with a taproot and fibrous roots</growthForm><size>to about 30 cm above water line</size><parts><part><partName>Roots</partName><partText>often growing from lower nodes.</partText></part><part><partName>Stem</partName><partText>hollow, cylindrical, erect to ascending or creeping, smooth.</partText></part><part><partName>Leaves</partName><partText>alternate, pinnately divided with three to nine leaflets, stalked (stalk partially clasping stem), to 15 cm long. Leaflets opposite to subopposite, stalkless, to 2 cm long, to 1 cm wide, egg- lance-shaped, bases oblique (with unequal sides), tips often notched, margins non-toothed to shallowly toothed, smooth. Terminal leaflet longest.</partText></part><part><partName>Flowers</partName><partText>in dense, branched clusters (raceme), which are borne terminally at the ends of shoots. Flower stalks 2 - 7 mm long, hairless. Sepals four, free (unattached), 3 mm long, 1.2 mm wide. Petals four, free (not attached), white, twice as long as sepals, bases narrowed. Stamens six. Anthers yellow.</partText></part><part><partName>Fruit</partName><partText>a long, narrow pod (silicle), widely spreading, 1 - 2.5 cm long, cylindrical, rounded in cross section, with a short beak. Seeds many, in two rows, coarse.</partText></part><part><partName/><partText/></part><part><partName/><partText/></part><part><partName/><partText/></part><part><partName/><partText/></part><part><partName/><partText/></part></parts></desc><similarSpecies><comments/><nameCds><simNmCd/><simNmCd/><simNmCd/><simNmCd/><simNmCd/><simNmCd/></nameCds><links><link><linkUri/><linkText/></link><link><linkUri/><linkText/></link></links></similarSpecies><flowering>Late April to mid-September</flowering><habitatEcology>Locally abundant in ditches and creeks. It also occurs in calcareous springs. May form large, tangled masses.</habitatEcology><nativity>non-native</nativity><notes><